[49m[38;5;10m+     1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 11.9: Care Coordination Assistant
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Complexity:** Complex · **Phase:** Regulated · **Estimated Cost:** ~$3-12 per active member per month (depends on engagement frequency, channel mix, model choice, RAG depth, integration depth across referral and chart-context systems, and care-management-staff escalation overhead)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Robert is 67. Robert had a heart attack on a Tuesday in March. He spent four days at the academic medical center across town, had two stents placed, was started on five new medications, and was discharged on a Saturday with a stack of paperwork that included, among other things, a discharge summary, prescriptions for those five new medications (one of which his usual pharmacy did not have in stock), a referral to a cardiologist for follow-up in two weeks, a referral to cardiac rehabilitation to start within four weeks, instructions to follow up with his primary care physician within seven days, instructions to schedule an echocardiogram at three months, instructions to have a fasting lipid panel and a basic metabolic panel drawn at one month, instructions to monitor his blood pressure daily and bring the readings to his cardiology follow-up, instructions about diet (low sodium, heart-healthy, with a pamphlet), instructions about activity (gradual increase, avoid lifting more than ten pounds for two weeks, no driving for one week), instructions about warning signs (chest pain, shortness of breath, weight gain of more than three pounds in a day, swelling in the legs), and a phone number to call with questions, which when Robert called it on Sunday went to a recording that said the line was open weekdays nine to five.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m What happened over the next eight weeks is the story of about eight hundred thousand Americans discharged after a cardiac event each year, and the broader story of the roughly thirty-five million U.S. patients who experience a care transition (hospital discharge, specialist referral, post-procedure follow-up, transition between insurance plans, transition between primary care providers) in any given year. <!-- TODO: verify; the CDC's National Hospital Discharge Survey and CMS data document U.S. hospital-discharge volumes; specific figures vary by year and methodology. The literature on care-transition volume and complexity is well-established but specific aggregate figures vary by source --> Robert called his usual pharmacy on Monday to fill the new prescriptions. The pharmacy had three of the five in stock. The fourth was a brand of clopidogrel his pharmacy could order but would take two days. The fifth, a sacubitril-valsartan combination, required a prior authorization that the discharging hospital had not obtained, which meant the pharmacy could not dispense it without contacting the prescribing hospitalist who was now off-shift, which meant Robert went home Monday with three of the five medications and a vague sense that something was wrong. Robert took the three medications. He did not take the two he could not get. He did not call anyone about it because he did not know who the right person to call was, and he did not want to seem like a complainer, and he was tired.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m On Tuesday Robert called the cardiologist's office to schedule his two-week follow-up. The cardiologist's first available appointment was in five weeks. The scheduler suggested Robert ask his primary care physician for a sooner appointment with someone else, but Robert's primary care physician's office did not have any cardiology appointments to schedule on his behalf. Robert took the five-week appointment. By Thursday Robert had also scheduled (after several phone calls) a primary care follow-up for the following Tuesday, an echocardiogram for the third week of June, and his lipid panel for the second week of April. The cardiac rehabilitation referral required Robert to call the rehabilitation center, which informed him that they had a four-week wait list and could schedule his intake assessment for late April. Robert wrote all of this down on a yellow legal pad in his kitchen. The legal pad had grown to three pages by Friday.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m What none of this captured, because it could not be captured by any one of these phone calls or appointments, was the fundamental fact that the system that had just saved Robert's life had also just abandoned him. The hospital that did the stents was now over. The hospitalist who managed his stay was now done. The cardiologist who would manage his ongoing cardiac care had not yet started, and would not start for five weeks. The primary care physician who was supposed to be the home base for everything had a Tuesday appointment scheduled but did not have access to Robert's discharge summary because the academic medical center's electronic record did not exchange data with Robert's primary care physician's electronic record reliably, and the hospital's discharge instructions had been faxed to a fax machine that the primary care physician's office had not actively used in three years. The pharmacy did not know Robert's prior authorization had not been obtained because Robert did not know to tell them. The cardiac rehabilitation program did not know Robert had been discharged because no one had told them yet. The lab where Robert was supposed to have his blood drawn at one month did not have a standing order. The seven-day post-discharge follow-up that the hospital's discharge instructions said Robert was supposed to have was not on anyone's calendar except Robert's, on his yellow legal pad, in his kitchen.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Six days after discharge, Robert noticed his ankles were swollen. The discharge instructions had said to watch for this. The discharge instructions had also said to call if it happened. Robert called the number on the discharge instructions. The number went to the recording. Robert did not know who else to call. Robert decided to wait until his Tuesday primary care appointment, which was the next day. At the Tuesday appointment, the primary care physician (who still did not have the discharge summary) listened to Robert describe his hospitalization, took his blood pressure (which was 178 over 102, much higher than it had been in the hospital), looked at the ankle swelling, and sent Robert directly to the emergency department of a different hospital. Robert was readmitted that afternoon for hypertensive urgency and likely under-titration of his heart-failure medications, the most concerning of which was the sacubitril-valsartan that he was supposed to be taking but had never received because of the prior authorization issue. Robert spent three more days in the hospital. The cardiologist who finally saw him on the second day of the readmission asked, with the careful tone clinicians use when they have already had this conversation many times, whether Robert had been taking all his medications. Robert said yes, three of the five. The cardiologist closed his eyes briefly. By the time Robert was discharged from this second admission, he had been re-prescribed the medications, the prior authorization had been obtained, the cardiology follow-up had been moved up to the following week, the cardiac rehabilitation intake had been expedited, and someone had finally arranged for the discharge summary to actually arrive at his primary care physician's office. Robert's outcome, in the long run, was actually fine. His outcome could have been very, very different.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is care coordination in the United States in 2026, and it is one of the largest sources of avoidable cost, avoidable hospitalization, avoidable mortality, and avoidable patient suffering in the entire healthcare system. The clinical knowledge required to manage Robert's transition was not exotic. The medications were standard. The follow-up plan was textbook. The warning signs were the warning signs the discharge instructions correctly identified. The reason Robert ended up readmitted was not that his care team did not know what to do; it was that no one was responsible for making sure all of it actually happened, in the correct sequence, with the correct information flowing to the correct people, and no one was checking on Robert during the most vulnerable thirty days of his recovery. Studies of post-discharge readmission rates have consistently identified care-transition gaps as one of the dominant drivers of avoidable readmission, with the rate of thirty-day readmission for Medicare patients hovering around fifteen percent across most years. <!-- TODO: verify; the CMS Hospital Readmissions Reduction Program publishes thirty-day readmission rates by condition and hospital; the Medicare-wide readmission rate has hovered around fifteen percent in recent years with substantial variation by condition; specific figures vary by year and population --> A meaningful fraction of those readmissions are attributable to care-coordination failures of the type Robert experienced. The math, as a system-design problem, is unforgiving.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The previous generations of care-coordination tools tried to address this in three waves. The first wave, roughly the 2000s through the early 2010s, was the nurse care manager, an actual human (almost always a registered nurse) employed by a payer or a health system to call patients after discharge, ask if they had their medications, ask if they had their follow-up appointments, and surface concerns to the clinical team. The clinical evidence for nurse care management was solid; the operational problem was that nurses are expensive, finite, and in shortage, and the staffing model could only reach a small fraction of the patients who needed support. <!-- TODO: verify; nurse care manager programs typically reach single-digit to low double-digit percentages of plan populations, focused on high-risk members based on cost predictors and clinical complexity; specific reach figures vary by payer and program design --> The second wave, roughly the early 2010s through the early 2020s, was the care-coordination platform, software that gave the nurse care manager a unified view of the patient and a worklist of post-discharge tasks. The software made the nurse more efficient, which expanded the reach modestly, but did not change the fundamental constraint that a human had to do the work. The third wave, starting around 2022, is conversational AI for care coordination, which is what this recipe is about, and which has the potential (carefully deployed) to extend the care-coordination workflow to the broad middle of the patient population that the nurse-care-management workforce alone cannot reach.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing to understand before building this is that the care coordination assistant is not a chatbot that answers questions about discharge instructions. The care coordination assistant is a system that holds, on behalf of the patient, the entire care plan across providers, ingests events as they happen (referrals placed, appointments scheduled, prescriptions filled, lab results posted, biometric readings logged, hospitalizations occurring), notices when expected events are missing (the prescription was never filled, the follow-up appointment was never scheduled, the cardiac rehabilitation intake never happened), engages the patient when engagement is needed (proactively reminding, asking about barriers, surfacing missing information), surfaces the right people when escalation is needed (the prior authorization is stuck, the patient is showing warning signs, the patient cannot afford the medication), and maintains the longitudinal context across episodes that the fragmented record system does not. The bot is the connective tissue that the system structurally lacks. The patient is the only person who experiences the full arc of their care; the bot is the only system that sees what the patient sees.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few things this recipe is and is not.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is the bot that maintains an ongoing relationship with a patient navigating a care episode (a discharge, a complex diagnosis, a surgical course, a chronic-condition exacerbation, a transition between providers or insurance plans), tracks the patient's referrals and follow-up schedule, ingests events across the patient's care continuum, engages the patient at appropriate moments, surfaces gaps and barriers, and escalates to human care managers and clinical teams when the situation warrants. The bot is owned by the institution's care-management or care-coordination program and operates within the boundaries of the institution's defined coordination protocols.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a chronic disease coach. Recipe 11.7 covers ongoing chronic-condition self-management, with biometric integration and behavior-change-stage tracking. The care coordination assistant addresses the navigation of care across providers and across transitions, with a focus on tracking the care plan's logistical execution rather than the patient's behavioral adherence to a chronic-condition self-management program. The two recipes are complementary; high-need patients often have both deployed.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a triage bot. Recipe 11.6 covers acute-symptom triage. The care coordination assistant routes acute-symptom presentations to triage workflows or directly to emergency routing rather than attempting triage from scratch.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a substitute for the care team or the human care manager. The bot extends the care team's reach. The bot handles the high-volume, lower-cognitive-load tasks (tracking the appointment was scheduled, reminding the patient about the appointment, asking about barriers, surfacing missing items), freeing the human care managers to focus on the complex cases. The patient still has their primary care physician, their specialists, their pharmacist, and (for higher-risk patients) their nurse care manager. The bot is not the care manager; the patient is told this explicitly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a one-size-fits-all product. A post-discharge care coordination assistant for a cardiac patient is structurally different from a care coordination assistant for an oncology patient navigating chemotherapy, which is different from one for a transplant patient managing complex immunosuppression and a multi-specialist team, which is different from one for a frail elder navigating geriatric care across multiple providers. Most institutions deploy a multi-pathway architecture with episode-specific protocols layered on a shared coordination core.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a regulatory afterthought. Patient-facing care-coordination software, particularly when it provides direct guidance about medications, follow-up timing, or warning-sign self-monitoring, sits on or close to the FDA Software-as-a-Medical-Device line. <!-- TODO: verify; the FDA's 2022 final guidance on Clinical Decision Support software addresses some patient-facing software categories; the regulatory positioning of care-coordination software depends on the specific recommendations and claims; the regulatory landscape continues to evolve --> The institutional regulatory team is involved from architectural design through ongoing post-market surveillance.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a quick win. The deployment timeline is measured in quarters, not sprints. The cross-system integration work (referral systems, scheduling systems, EHR, claims data, pharmacy data, lab results, care-management-platform integration) is multi-quarter. The coordination-protocol development is multi-quarter. The care-team workflow integration is multi-quarter. The outcome demonstration is multi-year. Institutions building this expecting fast time-to-value are usually disappointed.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing to understand before building this is that the bot's value is not in any individual conversation. The value is in the cumulative reduction of the gaps between the moments when human care touches the patient. A bot evaluated on per-conversation engagement is being evaluated on the wrong metric. A bot evaluated on the rate at which gaps are closed (prescriptions filled, follow-up appointments scheduled and kept, lab results returned and reviewed, warning signs surfaced and addressed, readmissions avoided), on the rate of catch of missing elements, on the time-to-resolution for stuck items, and on patient-reported support during the transition is being evaluated correctly. The architectural decisions follow from there.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Let's get into it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: Conversational Care Coordination Grounded In Cross-System Event Streams, Care Plans, and Escalation Pathways
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why Care Coordination Has Resisted Both Software and Conversational AI Until Recently
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Care coordination, as a clinical workflow, has been a phone-and-fax-and-paperwork problem for almost all of its history, with the small modernizations that have happened (electronic referrals, patient portals, secure messaging) layered on top of the underlying paper-and-phone infrastructure. The reason is structural. Care coordination is, fundamentally, the work of moving information among providers, payers, pharmacies, labs, and patients in a system that was not designed for the information to flow easily. The U.S. healthcare system has, by some measures, the most fragmented information infrastructure in any large industry. <!-- TODO: verify; the fragmentation of U.S. healthcare information infrastructure is well-documented in healthcare-policy literature; specific quantitative comparisons across industries vary by methodology --> Information that would, in another industry, be transmitted electronically and instantaneously is, in healthcare, often transmitted by fax, by phone call, by the patient physically carrying paper, or not transmitted at all. The reasons are partly historical (the system grew up before the information infrastructure existed and has not retrofitted), partly economic (information friction is, perversely, a revenue source for some actors), partly regulatory (HIPAA's complexity discourages information sharing for risk-averse organizations), and partly competitive (electronic record vendors have business reasons not to interoperate).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing that human care coordinators do, when they do this work well, is hold a longitudinal, cross-provider, cross-system model of the patient in their heads, supplemented by the various electronic and paper records they can access, and use this model to ensure that the right information arrives at the right place at the right time. The model includes "what was the discharge plan," "what referrals were placed," "did the patient actually get an appointment," "did the patient actually attend the appointment," "did the appointment result in the right next steps," "what prescriptions are pending," "what prior authorizations are stuck," "what lab orders are outstanding," "what warning signs is the patient experiencing," "what is the patient's current understanding of their plan," "what barriers does the patient have to following the plan," and "where is the next thing that needs to happen." Holding this model is most of the cognitive work. Producing the actual phone calls, faxes, and patient outreach is the easy part once the model is in place.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The first generation of care-coordination software, roughly the early 2000s through the early 2010s, tried to systematize the worklist part of this without the model part. The care coordinator got a list of post-discharge tasks to call patients about. The software did not know whether the tasks had actually been completed; the coordinator had to find out by calling. The software did not know whether the patient had any actual barriers; the coordinator had to ask. The software was a glorified to-do list. The clinical evidence for these tools was, broadly, that they made coordinators slightly more efficient. <!-- TODO: verify; the evidence base for first-generation care-coordination software is mixed and is documented in operational and quality-improvement literature; specific figures vary by program --> The fundamental problem these tools had was that they did not extend the coordinator's cognitive reach; they just systematized the calling.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The second generation, roughly 2015 to 2022, layered cross-system data integration on top of the worklist. The platform pulled scheduling data from the scheduling system, referral data from the referral system, prescription data from the pharmacy system, claims data from the payer, biometric data from connected devices, and assembled a longitudinal view that the coordinator could see at a glance. The clinical evidence for these platforms was more promising, and major payers and health systems invested heavily in care-management-platform deployment. <!-- TODO: verify; the evidence base for second-generation care-coordination platforms includes published studies of programs from major payers and health systems; specific figures vary --> The fundamental constraint, though, was similar: the platform made the coordinator more efficient, which expanded the reach somewhat, but did not change the fundamental constraint that a human had to do the work, and the staffing model could not reach the broad middle of the population that needed coordination.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing that changed the workflow shape is, again, large language models that can carry on a coherent, sustained, personalized conversation across multiple touchpoints over weeks and months, while being driven by a structured care-coordination-platform underneath. A care coordination assistant, deployed with careful institutional governance, can hold the longitudinal model the human coordinator holds (it has the integrated data feed, it has the conversation history, it has the care plan, it has the warning-sign list), can engage with the patient at the touchpoints where engagement is needed (gentle reminder, barrier inquiry, missing-element follow-up, warning-sign check-in, pre-appointment preparation, post-appointment follow-through), can scale to the broad middle of the population that human care management cannot reach, and can escalate to the human team when the situation warrants. The LLM is not a care manager. The LLM is, in the right product design, a tool that lets the care-coordination workflow operate at population scale.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The architectural shift is from "worklist-and-call" to "event-stream-driven-conversation-with-human-backstop." The bot's value is concentrated in three places: the cross-system event stream that lets the bot notice things the patient has not noticed (the prescription was never filled, the follow-up was never scheduled, the lab result is back and abnormal), the longitudinal personalized engagement that turns dozens of small touches across a care episode into measurable care-plan completion, and the operational reach that extends the care-management workforce from a few percent of the population to the broad middle.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What a Care Coordination Assistant Actually Does
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A care coordination assistant is a tool-using LLM with a system prompt that tells it which assistant it is, the patient's authenticated context (active care episodes, current care plan with pending items, current medications, current providers across the patient's care team, conversation history with the assistant over the episode, stated patient preferences), access to a structured library of episode-specific coordination protocols (post-discharge cardiac, post-discharge orthopedic, oncology induction, transplant maintenance, transition between insurance plans, others), and a careful set of tools for ingesting events from cross-system feeds, retrieving the patient's current plan items, surfacing missing or stuck items, sending follow-up messages, and escalating to clinical and care-management staff. The LLM conducts the conversations. The structured care plan, the cross-system event integration, and the coordination-protocol corpus encode the operational logic. The tools handle the deterministic actions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The conversation surface is, again, not one conversation. It is a stream of conversational episodes across the duration of the care episode, sometimes initiated by the patient, sometimes initiated by the assistant per a protocol-driven schedule, sometimes triggered by an event (a referral was placed, an appointment was scheduled, an appointment was missed, a prescription was not filled, a lab result is abnormal, a hospitalization occurred elsewhere), and sometimes triggered by a missing-event detection (a referral that was supposed to result in an appointment within 14 days has not done so).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The assistant's task surface decomposes roughly as follows.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Onboarding into a care episode.** The patient is enrolled in coordination support by their care team, by an automated trigger (discharge from a hospitalization, placement of a complex referral, initiation of a high-risk care plan), or by self-enrollment through the institution's portal. The first conversation introduces the assistant, sets expectations (the assistant tracks the care plan, is not a doctor, is not a substitute for the care team, is reachable for questions about the plan, escalates to humans when needed), gathers stated preferences (preferred check-in cadence, preferred channels, language, things the patient does not want to discuss, quiet hours), and confirms the patient's understanding of the care plan as it stands. The onboarding tone is warm but boundaried; the assistant is a tool deployed by the patient's care team.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-system event ingestion.** Throughout the care episode, the assistant ingests events from the institution's referral system (referrals placed, scheduled, completed, declined), scheduling system (appointments scheduled, kept, missed, cancelled, rescheduled), EHR (encounters, problem-list updates, medication-list updates, lab orders, lab results, imaging orders, imaging results, discharge summaries from external facilities where exchange permits), claims data (where consented and where the institutional integration permits, encounter notifications and external-facility hospitalizations), pharmacy data (prescriptions filled, prior authorizations, refills due, refills missed), and biometric data (where consented and where devices are integrated). Each event is matched to the patient's active care plan, evaluated for whether it represents a planned event, an unplanned event, or a missing event that should have happened.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient-initiated questions about the plan.** The patient can engage at any time with questions about their plan, their medications, their appointments, what they are supposed to be doing next, who they should call about a specific issue, what to do about a barrier (the medication is too expensive, the appointment time conflicts with work, the office is too far away, the language was unclear, the form is confusing). The assistant answers within scope, escalates outside scope (acute symptom routes to triage, new clinical concern routes to the care team, complex benefits or authorization issue routes to the benefits navigator or to the care manager, language-services need routes to interpreter services).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Proactive coordination touchpoints.** The assistant runs scheduled touchpoints per the episode's coordination protocol: post-discharge day-2 wellness check, post-discharge day-7 progress check, pre-appointment preparation 24-48 hours before each scheduled appointment, post-appointment follow-up the day after each appointment, prescription-refill nudge before each medication runs out, missing-action escalation when an expected event has not occurred within the protocol's window. The cadence is determined by the protocol, not by the LLM.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Gap and barrier detection.** When the cross-system event stream shows that an expected event has not happened within the protocol's window (the prescription was sent but not filled in 5 days; the referral was placed but no appointment was scheduled in 14 days; the patient missed the cardiac rehabilitation intake; the lab result has not come back when it was due), the assistant engages. The first touchpoint asks about barriers (was there a problem at the pharmacy; have you been able to reach the cardiologist's office; is there something making this hard). Based on the patient's response, the assistant either resolves the barrier within scope (provides the right phone number, sends the right reminder, escalates the prior authorization), or routes to the appropriate human resource (care manager for benefits issues, social-work navigation for transportation or housing-related barriers, pharmacist for medication-cost issues, clinical team for symptom-related concerns).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Warning-sign monitoring.** Each care episode has a defined set of warning signs (chest pain in the cardiac patient, fever and chills in the post-surgical patient, neutropenia symptoms in the chemotherapy patient, suicidal ideation in the postpartum-discharge patient). The assistant screens for warning signs continuously and routes positive screens immediately, with stay-and-bridge support similar to the patterns established in the previous chapter 11 recipes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-team coordination and information transmission.** When the assistant identifies a finding the care team should know about (a barrier that needs care-management attention, a warning sign that needs clinical evaluation, a patient-reported outcome that should inform the next visit, a non-adherence pattern), the assistant generates a structured note for the care-team workflow and routes it to the appropriate clinician with the conversation context attached. The assistant does not modify the clinical record without institutional approval; it generates messages and structured findings for clinician review.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-provider information bridging.** Where information has not flowed between providers (the discharge summary did not arrive at the primary care physician's office; the specialist's recommendations did not reach the primary care physician; the pharmacist does not know about the new diagnosis), the assistant flags the gap, surfaces the patient as the connective tissue, and (where institutional integration permits) initiates the cross-provider information exchange. Where it does not, the assistant prepares the patient with the right talking points and the right documents to bring to the next provider visit.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Long-term episode tracking.** The episode has a defined start (discharge, diagnosis, procedure, transition) and a defined end (discharge from coordination support, completion of the protocol, transfer to chronic-condition coaching, return to baseline). Throughout, the assistant maintains the longitudinal view of where the patient is in the protocol, what is complete, what is pending, what is at risk, and what needs human attention.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Off-boarding from coordination support.** When the protocol is complete, when the patient transitions to chronic-condition coaching (recipe 11.7) or returns to baseline care, when the patient prefers human-only support, the assistant supports a respectful transition with structured summary delivery to the patient's care team and a clear path back if the patient needs support again.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[K
Creating: [38;5;141mC:\tmp\ralph-worktrees\iter-375\chapter11.09-care-coordination-assistant.md[0m
[38;5;244m - Completed in 0.17s[0m

I'll append content to file: [38;5;141mchapter11.09-care-coordination-assistant.md[0m[38;5;244m (using tool: write)[0m
Purpose: Append technology section continuation

[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why a Generic LLM Cannot Run a Care Coordination Assistant
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A naive product approach would be: take a generalist LLM, give it a chat surface, paste in a discharge summary, and have it answer the patient's questions about their plan. This breaks in several specific ways, each of which has clinical and operational consequences.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no view of cross-system reality.** The patient's plan does not live in the LLM's prompt. The plan lives in the referral system, the scheduling system, the EHR, the pharmacy system, the labs system, the claims system, and (for some events) the patient's own self-reports. Without integrated event ingestion, the LLM is operating on a discharge summary that was a snapshot at the moment of discharge and has been progressively diverging from reality ever since. The cross-system event integration is the architectural primitive that distinguishes the coordination assistant from a chatbot answering questions about static instructions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of what should have happened by now.** The coordination protocols specify what should happen and when (the prior authorization should be obtained within 48 hours; the post-discharge primary care follow-up should be scheduled within seven days; the cardiac rehabilitation intake should occur within four weeks; the one-month lab follow-up should be drawn at week 4). Without the protocol as input, the LLM has no basis to flag "this should have happened by now." The protocol-as-code with named ownership is essential.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model hallucinates institutional details when grounding is weak.** If the institutional coordination protocols, contact directories, formularies, and authorization processes are not retrieved with strict citation grounding, the LLM produces plausible-sounding instructions that are wrong for the institution. The assistant tells the patient to call a number that does not exist or to ask for a person who does not work there. The institution-specific RAG layer with strict citation grounding is non-negotiable.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of when to engage proactively.** The bot's value depends substantially on proactive engagement triggered by events and missing-events. A reactive bot that only responds when the patient initiates is doing about a third of the job. The proactive engagement scheduling is encoded in the coordination protocols and triggered by the event-ingestion pipeline, not by the LLM.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of escalation routing.** When the patient discloses a symptom that warrants emergency evaluation, when the pharmacy issue is actually a stuck prior authorization that needs human intervention, when the patient cannot afford the medication, when the patient has a transportation barrier to the appointment, when the patient discloses suicidal ideation in the post-discharge wellness check, when a follow-up gap has gone past the protocol's tolerance, the response is not "let me give you some general advice." The response is to route, with the appropriate human resource selected based on the issue type. The escalation routing is encoded explicitly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of patient-as-narrator-versus-systems-of-record.** Patients sometimes report things that the systems of record contradict (the patient says they have an appointment that the scheduling system has no record of; the patient says they took their medication that the pharmacy system shows was never filled). The assistant has to handle the discrepancy with care: not call the patient a liar, not assume the systems are right, and route the discrepancy to the appropriate human resource with the conversation context. The system-of-record-versus-patient-report reconciliation pattern is part of the architecture.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has clinical-decision-rule arithmetic problems.** Care coordination occasionally surfaces clinical decision rules (CHA2DS2-VASc for atrial fibrillation, HAS-BLED, bone-mineral-density follow-up timing, blood-pressure-medication titration windows, post-cardiac-rehabilitation timing). The LLM does this poorly. The deterministic clinical-rule tools encapsulate the computation; the LLM gathers the inputs and presents the result with the institutional-standard interpretation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has compliance implications specific to care coordination.** The conversation contains PHI, often dense and longitudinal, often referencing multiple providers across multiple organizations. Some interactions surface intimate-partner violence, food insecurity, substance use, mental-health crisis, and abuse disclosures. The audit, retention, access-control, mandatory-reporting, and downstream-clinical-workflow integration story has to handle each.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of staying within scope when the patient asks for clinical advice.** Patients in coordination relationships frequently ask things like "should I take this medication if I am also taking that one," "is this lab result okay," "should I be worried about this symptom," "should I have this surgery." The assistant answers within scope (the plan, the logistics, the institution-stated talking points), escalates outside scope (the clinical decisions, the diagnostic interpretations, the treatment recommendations), and does not pretend to be a clinician.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of when the coordination relationship should end.** Some episodes complete and the patient transitions out of coordination support. Some patients move to chronic-condition coaching. Some patients prefer human-only care. Off-boarding is part of the protocol, with named off-boarding events, summary delivery, and respectful closure of the conversational relationship.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of multi-organization data flow.** Care coordination, by its nature, spans organizations. The patient's primary care physician and specialist are often in different organizations with different EHRs. The patient's pharmacy is a different organization. The patient's payer is a different organization. The information-sharing posture across organizations has its own consent posture, its own legal posture, and its own technical-integration constraints. The architecture has to handle this; the LLM does not.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What the Coordination Assistant Has To Do That the Previous Bots Did Not
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Recipes 11.1 through 11.8 established the patterns this recipe inherits: input safety screening with continuous emergency screening, identity verification, tool-use orchestration, output safety screening, audit logging, per-cohort monitoring, scope discipline, prompt-injection defense, graceful degradation, longitudinal-context loading, citation grounding, behavior-change-stage tracking, crisis screening, warm handoff. The care coordination assistant adds eight structural commitments those recipes did not have.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-system event ingestion as architectural primitive.** The assistant subscribes to events from the referral system, scheduling system, EHR, claims, pharmacy, labs, biometric devices, and care-management platform. Each event updates the patient's active care plan state. Missing-event detection runs continuously against the protocol's expected timeline.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Coordination-protocol-as-code with named ownership.** Each care episode type (post-discharge cardiac, post-discharge orthopedic, oncology induction, transplant maintenance, transition between insurance plans, others) has a structured protocol defining the events that should happen, the timing windows, the touchpoints, the warning signs, the escalation criteria, and the off-boarding criteria. The protocols are owned by the institution's care-management leadership, version-controlled, and reviewed regularly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-organization information bridging.** The assistant operates across organizational boundaries. The data-sharing posture, the consent posture, and the technical-integration constraints across organizations are part of the architecture, not afterthoughts.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-team workflow integration with structured handoff payloads.** The assistant generates structured findings for the care team rather than raw conversation transcripts. The care manager, the primary care physician, the specialist, and the pharmacist each have specific information needs; the assistant produces handoffs designed for each role's workflow.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient-as-narrator versus system-of-record reconciliation.** Where the patient's reports and the systems of record disagree, the assistant has a defined reconciliation pattern: log the discrepancy, route to the appropriate human resource, do not assume either side is wrong without further information.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Episode-level tracking as architectural primitive.** The episode has a defined start, a defined end, and a defined trajectory. The assistant tracks the patient's position in the protocol, the protocol's completion percentage, the at-risk items, and the time-to-completion estimate. The episode-level view is the unit of clinical and operational analysis, not the conversation-level view.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcome-correlation pipeline focused on care-coordination outcomes.** The assistant's clinical performance is measured against actual care-coordination outcomes: thirty-day readmission rate, prescription-fill rate, follow-up-appointment-attendance rate, gap-closure rate, time-to-resolution for stuck items, patient-reported coordination quality, downstream avoidable-event rate.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **FDA-strategy alignment as architectural constraint.** Patient-facing coordination software, particularly when it makes warning-sign-related recommendations and when it triggers self-monitoring behavior, sits on or close to the FDA SaMD line. The institutional regulatory team is involved.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The rest is largely the same as the previous chapter 11 recipes: tool-surface contract management, identity-assurance lifecycle, conversation logging, scope filtering, per-cohort monitoring, graceful degradation when upstream systems fail.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The Coordination-Assistant Reality
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few notes on what makes care coordination specifically harder than the other patient-facing bot use cases.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The cross-system integration work is the project.** The bot itself is not the hard part. The hard part is integrating with the institution's referral system, scheduling system, EHR (often multiple EHRs), claims data, pharmacy systems, labs systems, care-management platform, and patient-portal infrastructure. Most of the engineering investment, and most of the deployment timeline, is in the integration. Institutions that underestimate this consistently miss timelines.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-organization integration is the harder version of the same work.** The patient's care does not happen entirely within the institution. The primary care physician may be in a different system. The specialist may be in a different system. The pharmacy is in a different system. The payer is in a different system. Cross-organization data exchange in the U.S. is, charitably, immature. <!-- TODO: verify; the state of cross-organization health data exchange in the U.S. is documented in ONC reports and trade-press coverage; specific quantitative findings vary --> Architectures that work entirely within one organization often fail to extend across organizations. The TEFCA framework, USCDI standards, and FHIR-based exchange are improving the situation but do not yet solve it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The protocol library is the core clinical asset.** Each episode-type has its own protocol with its own touchpoints, timing windows, warning signs, and escalation criteria. Building the protocol library is multi-quarter clinical work that has to start before the engineering work and continue alongside it. Most institutions discover, partway through, that their existing care-management protocols are not in a form that supports digital execution and need substantial rework.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Engagement attrition has different drivers than chronic-disease coaching.** The coordination relationship is bounded by the episode (typically 30-90 days for a discharge episode, longer for a complex care plan). Attrition over an episode is less of an issue than in long-term chronic-condition coaching, but the episode's first 24-72 hours are the most engagement-critical and also the most fragile.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The bot is more transactional and less relational than the chronic-disease coach or the mental-health support bot.** Many coordination touchpoints are short and specific (the prescription was sent; have you filled it; if not, what is the barrier). The relationship-quality engineering still matters, but the calibration is different from a multi-year coaching relationship; warmth in a coordination context is more like a competent administrative assistant than a long-term coach.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The bot's value is heavily concentrated in the gaps and stuck items.** Most patients in a coordination episode do not need much active engagement; their care is on track. The patients who need the bot most are the patients with stuck prior authorizations, missed follow-ups, transportation barriers, language barriers, financial barriers, or other social-determinants barriers. Per-cohort monitoring with explicit equity focus is essential.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Social-determinants integration is structurally part of the architecture.** Patients with transportation barriers, food insecurity, housing instability, cost-of-medication concerns, or limited English proficiency need handoffs to specific resources. The coordination assistant integrates with the institution's social-determinants screening, with care-navigation services, with community-based-organization referrals, with financial-assistance programs, and with interpreter services. <!-- TODO: verify; the integration of social-determinants screening into care coordination is documented in CMS guidance and care-management literature; specific implementation patterns vary --> A coordination assistant that does not integrate with social-determinants services is a coordination assistant that only serves the patients with the fewest barriers.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The downstream-event prevention metric is multi-quarter to multi-year work.** The dominant ROI for care coordination comes from reducing avoidable hospitalizations, avoidable ED visits, and other downstream events. The metric demonstration takes time and requires careful attribution analysis with appropriate controls. Institutions building this with quarterly-impact expectations will be disappointed; institutions willing to invest at the right time horizon can demonstrate genuinely meaningful outcomes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-condition complexity is the norm.** Most patients in coordination support have multiple things going on. A post-discharge cardiac patient is often also a diabetic, often also a hypertensive, often also has chronic kidney disease, often also has depression, often is on twelve medications. The coordination assistant has to maintain coherent context across the patient's full clinical picture, even when the immediate episode is one specific event. Most production deployments start with episode-specific focus and add multi-condition coherence over time.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-team-bot integration is a specific architectural and operational discipline.** The care managers, the primary care physicians, the specialists, the pharmacists, and the social workers each have to know what the bot does, when to expect findings from it, and how to feed back when the bot's findings are wrong. Building this without the care team's active involvement produces a bot the care team does not use, which is an expensive failure mode.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient consent across the episode lifecycle matters.** The patient enrolled (or was enrolled) at the start of the episode. The patient retains the right to opt out, dial back engagement, restrict topics, restrict providers from getting findings, and revoke consent. The institutional consent posture is reviewed by legal and compliance teams, reflects state-specific requirements, and is operationally enforced.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Liability exposure for missed escalations is real.** A bot that fails to surface a warning sign during a post-discharge wellness check, and a patient who is subsequently harmed, is a foreseeable liability exposure. The institutional malpractice carrier is part of the policy review; the warning-sign-detection sensitivity is the launch-gate metric for episode types where warning signs are clinically critical.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Where the Field Has Moved
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few practical updates worth knowing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Hospital readmission penalties continue to drive investment.** The CMS Hospital Readmissions Reduction Program penalizes hospitals with above-expected thirty-day readmission rates for several specific conditions (heart failure, acute myocardial infarction, pneumonia, COPD, hip and knee replacement, coronary artery bypass graft surgery). <!-- TODO: verify; the CMS HRRP program targets specific conditions and uses condition-specific risk-adjusted readmission rates; the program continues to evolve with periodic adjustments --> Coordination programs that demonstrably reduce readmissions in these populations have a clear ROI argument.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **TEFCA-based exchange is improving cross-organization data access.** The Trusted Exchange Framework and Common Agreement, with Qualified Health Information Networks operational since 2024, provides a national framework for healthcare data exchange. <!-- TODO: verify; TEFCA implementation has continued since the 2024 operational launch with QHINs onboarding and use-case expansion; specific reach and capability vary --> Coordination assistants increasingly have access to data from external organizations that were previously unreachable.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **FHIR-native EHR integration is now feasible at most major systems.** The FHIR standard, with bulk-FHIR for population-level extracts and SMART-on-FHIR for embedded application access, is widely deployed across major EHRs. <!-- TODO: verify; FHIR API support is required by ONC certification and is widely available across major EHRs; specific capability and reliability vary --> Coordination assistants that previously had to use HL7 V2 messaging, fax, or screen-scraping increasingly use FHIR APIs.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Tool-using LLMs handle coordination workflows well when grounded carefully.** The function-calling pattern from previous chapter 11 recipes maps to coordination. The LLM produces tool calls that retrieve protocol items, retrieve scheduling status, retrieve prescription status, retrieve referral status, retrieve lab results, surface gap items, send follow-up messages, and post events for downstream operations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Hybrid AI-plus-human coordination is the dominant production pattern.** Most major deployments run a hybrid model: AI assistant for the broad coordination majority, with human care managers available for the complex cases, escalation cases, and patient-requested human contact. The economics work because the AI handles the routine touches while the human focuses on the cases that need clinical or social judgment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcome demonstration is mixed but trending positive for hybrid models.** Studies of digital-plus-human care-coordination programs have shown statistically and clinically meaningful improvements in readmission rates, follow-up adherence, prescription-fill rates, and patient-reported coordination quality, with the magnitude of effect varying by program design, episode type, and population. <!-- TODO: verify; the evidence base for hybrid digital care-coordination programs includes published studies of programs from major payers and health systems with effect sizes varying by program --> The ROI demonstrations are stronger when the analysis includes downstream-event reduction than when the analysis focuses on direct engagement metrics.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Equity considerations are a major area of attention.** Studies of digital health tools have documented variability in adoption, engagement, and outcomes by patient demographics, with the concern that the patients who most need coordination support (often elderly, often non-English-speaking, often low-income, often with limited digital access) are the patients who least benefit from digital deployment. <!-- TODO: verify; disparities in digital health tool adoption have been documented in multiple studies including those by Nouri et al. 2020, the Pew Research Center, and others --> Per-cohort monitoring is essential. Multi-channel deployment (chat, SMS, voice, multilingual) is essential.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Build-vs-buy is mature for some segments.** Several care-coordination platform vendors operate at major-payer and major-health-system scale, with EHR integration, referral-system integration, and (in some cases) AI-powered patient outreach. Most major institutions run a hybrid: build a thin orchestration layer in-house, partner with vendors for episode-specific protocols and for the human-care-manager workforce.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
