[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    599[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    600[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    601[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few cross-cutting design points specific to the care coordination assistant.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    602[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    603[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-system event integration as architectural primitive.** The assistant subscribes to events from referral, scheduling, EHR, claims, pharmacy, labs, biometric devices, and care-management platform feeds. Each event updates the patient's active care-plan state. Missing-event detection runs continuously against the protocol's expected timeline.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    604[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    605[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Coordination-protocol-as-code with named ownership.** Each episode-type's protocol is structured, version-controlled, owned by care-management leadership, and reviewed regularly. Each protocol item has an effective date and an annual review schedule.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    606[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    607[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-organization information bridging.** The assistant operates across organizational boundaries. Cross-organization data exchange uses TEFCA where available, FHIR APIs where available, and falls back to patient-as-narrator and structured information bridging where it is not.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    608[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    609[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient-as-narrator versus system-of-record reconciliation.** Where patient reports and systems of record disagree, the assistant logs the discrepancy, routes to the appropriate human resource, and does not assume either side is wrong without further information.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    610[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    611[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Episode-level tracking as architectural primitive.** The episode is the unit of clinical and operational analysis. The assistant tracks the patient's position in the protocol, completion percentage, at-risk items, and time-to-completion estimate.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    612[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    613[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Warning-sign monitoring with episode-specific lists.** Each protocol carries its own warning-sign list with validated language and clinical-leadership review. Continuous screening runs on every utterance.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    614[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    615[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Citation discipline as architectural primitive.** Every protocol-grounded response, every institution-specific instruction, every patient-education content delivery is grounded in a cited source.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    616[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    617[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Conservative-bias-default policy.** When the assistant is uncertain, when the patient's responses are ambiguous, when the conversation drifts toward clinical advice, the response defaults to "let me connect you with your care team."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    618[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    619[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Per-cohort monitoring is non-negotiable.** Engagement rate, plan-completion rate, stuck-item rate, time-to-resolution, warning-sign rates, and outcome metrics vary by episode type, language, channel, age cohort, sex, and social-determinant flags.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    620[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    621[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Disaster-recovery topology.** When the cross-system feeds, the protocol store, the warning-sign classifier, or any escalation pathway is unreachable, the assistant degrades gracefully. The minimum behavior is "I'm having trouble reaching some of your information right now; if this is an emergency please call 911" with direct routing to escalation resources. Graceful degradation paths are exercised in tabletop drills.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    622[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
